ion of biblical narratives, they also appropriated biblical tropes to their own ends. These innovative case-studies throw new light on familiar areas such as slavery, colonialism and the missionary project, while forging exciting cross-comparisons between race, identity and the politics of biblical translation and interpretation in South Africa, Egypt, Australia, America and Ireland.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImperialismxReligious aspects. 0aRacexBiblical teaching. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2020. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aBible.  aChristianity.  aColonial.  aEmpire.  aMissionaries.  aNationalism.  aPostcolonial.  aRace.  aReligion.  aTranslation.1 aAtkins, Gareth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtkins, Gareth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBatalden, Stephen K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarey, Hilary M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoffey, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDas, Shinjini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDas, Shinjini, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFigueira, Dorothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaynes, Stephen R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLivingstone, David N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonald, Jared, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, Brian H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, Brian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSharkey, Heather J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g